2. SQL Basics¶

Setting up the conda env:

conda create -n sql python
conda activate sql
conda install ipython-sql sqlalchemy psycopg2 notebook pandas -c conda-forge

Sample dataset:

  • cities.csv

  • countries.csv

2.1. Connecting to the database¶

%load_ext sql

import os

host = "localhost"
database = "sdb"
user = os.getenv('SQL_USER')
password = os.getenv('SQL_PASSWORD')

connection_string = f"postgresql://{user}:{password}@{host}/{database}"

%sql $connection_string

%%sql 

SELECT * FROM cities LIMIT 10

 * postgresql://postgres:***@localhost/sdb
10 rows affected.
id name country latitude longitude population
1 Bombo UGA 0.5833 32.5333 75000
2 Fort Portal UGA 0.671 30.275 42670
3 Potenza ITA 40.642 15.799 69060
4 Campobasso ITA 41.563 14.656 50762
5 Aosta ITA 45.737 7.315 34062
6 Mariehamn ALD 60.097 19.949 10682

2.4. SQL Joins¶

Reference: https://www.w3schools.com/sql/sql_join.asp

Here are the different types of the JOINs in SQL:

  • (INNER) JOIN: Returns records that have matching values in both tables

  • LEFT (OUTER) JOIN: Returns all records from the left table, and the matched records from the right table

  • RIGHT (OUTER) JOIN: Returns all records from the right table, and the matched records from the left table

  • FULL (OUTER) JOIN: Returns all records when there is a match in either left or right table

%%sql 

SELECT COUNT(*) FROM cities

 * postgresql://postgres:***@localhost/sdb
1 rows affected.
count
1249 
%%sql 

SELECT * FROM cities LIMIT 10

2.4.2. SQL Left Join¶

%%sql

SELECT * FROM cities LEFT JOIN countries ON cities.country = countries."Alpha3_code"

2.4.3. SQL Right Join¶

%%sql

SELECT * FROM cities RIGHT JOIN countries ON cities.country = countries."Alpha3_code"

SELECT country FROM cities
UNION 
SELECT "Alpha3_code" FROM countries

2.5. Aggregation¶

2.5.1. Group By¶

%%sql

SELECT COUNT(name), country 
FROM cities 
GROUP BY country 
ORDER BY COUNT(name) DESC

SELECT countries."Country", COUNT(name)
FROM cities
LEFT JOIN countries ON cities.country = countries."Alpha3_code"
GROUP BY countries."Country"
ORDER BY COUNT(name) DESC

2.5.2. Having¶

%%sql 

SELECT COUNT(name), country
FROM cities
GROUP BY country
HAVING COUNT(name) > 40
ORDER BY COUNT(name) DESC

 * postgresql://postgres:***@localhost/sdb

2.6. Conditional statements¶

%%sql

SELECT name, population,
CASE
    WHEN population > 10000000 THEN 'Megacity'
    WHEN population > 1000000 THEN 'Large city'
    ELSE 'Small city'
END AS category
FROM cities

2.7. Saving results¶

%%sql

SELECT *
INTO cities_new
FROM cities

 * postgresql://postgres:***@localhost/sdb

1249 rows affected.

[]

%%sql

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS cities_usa;

SELECT *
INTO cities_usa
FROM cities
WHERE country = 'USA'

 * postgresql://postgres:***@localhost/sdb
Done.
114 rows affected.

[]

%%sql 

INSERT INTO cities_usa
SELECT *
FROM cities
WHERE country = 'CAN'

 * postgresql://postgres:***@localhost/sdb
45 rows affected.

[]

2.8. SQL Comments¶

2.8.1. Single line coments¶

%%sql

SELECT * FROM cities LIMIT 10 -- This is a comment;

 * postgresql://postgres:***@localhost/sdb
10 rows affected.
id name country latitude longitude population
1 Bombo UGA 0.5833 32.5333 75000
2 Fort Portal UGA 0.671 30.275 42670
3 Potenza ITA 40.642 15.799 69060

5 Aosta ITA 45.737 7.315 34062
6 Mariehamn ALD 60.097 19.949 10682

9 Poitier FRA 46.58329 0.33328 85960
10 Clermont-Ferrand FRA 45.77998 3.08001 233050

2.8.2. Multi-line comments¶

%%sql

SELECT COUNT(name), country 
FROM cities 
/*
 * Adding Group by
 * Adding Order by
 */
GROUP BY country 
ORDER BY COUNT(name) DESC
LIMIT 10

 * postgresql://postgres:***@localhost/sdb
10 rows affected.
count country
